<font color="#FF0000">OLD GUILT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 29 13:32:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
&quot;The Pilot's Picnic&quot;<br><br>
Moist brown eyes that pierce the wire<br>
are framed by soft round faces.<br>
Through dust and stench and filth mire<br>
they scramble to claim their places.<br><br>
Row upon row they desperately grope<br>
into the sharp and twisted strands.<br>
Each little heart is pounding with hope<br>
in a sea of outstretched hands.<br><br>
&quot;Mai toi toi day, Dai-uy,&quot; they say,<br>
&quot;We are very hungry, Captain.&quot;<br>
I turn slowly and walk away,<br>
as they wonder what will happen.<br><br>
But nagging hunger holds in check<br>
small dirty feet, bent on fleeing.<br>
&quot;What is he lifting from the cargo deck?<br>
Can we believe what we are seeing?&quot;<br><br>
I say, &quot;Babysans first!&quot; in Vietnamese,<br>
tearing open the cardboard cases.<br>
The smallest emerge from a tangle of knees;<br>
pitiful, precious, sweet baby faces.<br><br>
With utmost care, I pass the fare<br>
past barbs of rusty steel<br>
And little tan cheeks buldge and flare<br>
as they relish a Spartan's meal.<br><br>
In stifling heat, they cherish meat,<br>
dug from green, greasy tins.<br>
First, one timid smile, then after a while<br>
I am engulfed by grateful grins.<br><br>
I say, &quot;Sin Loi,&quot; to a little boy,<br>
who pleads with a fervent zeal.<br>
The gunner's hand quells the demand, <br>
as he forfeits his evening meal.<br><br>
Then, all too soon, the cupboard is bare<br>
and I gather up paper and cans,<br>
wishing in vain  that I had more to share,<br>
among moist brown eyes and outstretched hands.<br><br>
From &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; Copyright 1990 Edward Ramon
